      "Process_Info": {
        "Process_Category": "Laser-Aided Additive Manufacturing (LAAM)",
        "Process_Text": {
          "original": "Multi-principal element alloys were fabricated using LAAM, integrating a Kuka robotic system, Precise laser head, Sulzer metco twin powder feeder, and an IPG ytterbium fiber laser system. Pre-alloyed CoCrNi and CoCrNiAl0.6TiFe powders were prepared via gas atomization, particle sizes ranging from 15 to 45 μm. Process optimization yielded the following parameters: 1.3 mm beam diameter, 570 W laser power, 5.4 g·min⁻¹ total powder feed rate, and 1200 mm·min⁻¹ scan velocity. The deposit layer was around 0.5 mm thickness, with a 90° rotation between adjacent layers. The overlap rate was 50% and argon gas (purity ≥99.999%) was used for shielding and powder transport. For CoCrNi, 100% CoCrNi powder was fed.",
          "simplified": "LAAM using 570 W laser, 1200 mm/min scan speed, 1.3 mm spot, 0.5 mm layer thickness, 50% overlap, Ar shield, 100% CoCrNi powder."
        },
        "Equipment": "Kuka robotic system with IPG fiber laser, Sulzer metco twin powder feeder",
        "Key_Params": {
          "Laser_Power_W": 570,
          "Scanning_Speed_mm_s": 20,
          "Layer_Thickness_um": 500,
          "Hatch_Spacing_um": null,
          "Spot_Size_um": 1300,
